en in Walled Societies: A Comparative Analysis of Iranian Film (The May Lady) and Chinese Film (Army Nurse) -- tPart IV Fact, Fiction, and Society -- t10. Rakhshan Banietemad’s Art of Social Realism: Bridging Realism and Fiction -- t11. Embracing All My Trees: An Ecocritical Reading -- t12. Hidden Transcripts of Subordinates and the Art of Resistance in Our Times -- tFilmography -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOffers the first English language book on the films and the career of Iranian director Rakhshan BanietemadDevotes specific attention to Banietemad’s long career in documentary filmmaking, which has been neglected in much of the scholarly works thus farIncludes chapters by some of the most prominent scholars of Iranian cinema as well as younger scholars with fresh points of viewSituates Banietemad among world auteurs while still looking at her works within the Iranian contextIncludes an in-depth interview with the directorRakhshan Banietemad is one of the first female film directors in Iran. This book, the first English language study of her films and career, Iranian director Rakhshan Banietemad contains chapters by some of the most prominent scholars of Iranian cinema, as well as younger scholars with fresh points of view. Taking an interdisciplinary perspective, the book devotes special attention to Banietemad’s understudied documentaries and films, including Under the Skin of the City (2000) and Tales (2014), while offering new perspectives on well-known works such as The Blue Veiled (1994) and The May Lady (1997). Focusing on questions of aesthetics and poetics, social realism, gender dynamics and the ‘afterimages’ and ‘counter-memories’ of revolution and war, the book also includes an in depth interview with Banietemad herself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF 